{{anchor|Lover's leap}}
The general message that emerges from the above table can be summarised as follows: unless one can make a point, and with the exception of the running move 24/13 (in which, having thrown a 6-5, the player moves a piece from the 24-point to the 13-point; the ''lover's leap''), a successful play is often the combination of splitting the 24-point and moving a checker from the 13-point. The latter move should be as small as possible (resulting in a builder close to the 13-point), unless the stack at the 8-point can be reached (resulting in an equal distribution between the 13-point and the 8-point).  However, there are plenty of exceptions to this rule; for example, a 4-3 or 3-2 is often best played by moving two checkers from the 13 point.<ref name=survey>[http://www.bkgm.com/openings.html Survey of opening rolls by Tom Keith on Backgammon Galore]</ref>

The above opening moves which emerged from computer analysis demonstrate that a number of opening moves that were unquestioned for many decades are now considered suboptimal. One example is the move 13/11-13/8 on the roll 5-2. Although not a bad move, the alternative choice preferred by the analyses, 24/22-13/8, is now generally agreed upon to be optimal. In other cases, computer analysis has resulted in alternative strategies that were not seriously considered in the past. For instance, the opening move 8/2-6/2 for a roll of 6-4 was in the past greeted with disdain from experts (making the 2-point instead of trying for a higher home point), but turns out to be on average as effective as the usual plays (24/14 and 24/18-13/9).


==Influencing factors==
The  opening moves above apply to money play, meaning that these plays optimise the expected payout with gammons counting double, etc. In match play the match score affects the checker play and one of the alternative plays may come out on top in computer simulations depending on the score.<ref> BGOnline.org Opening Moves AtS  http://bgonline.org/1ats/index.html</ref>  <ref>[http://www.bkgm.com/rgb/rgb.cgi?view+682 Kit Woolsey: Factors to consider in opening moves]</ref> In a "Gammon-go" situation the player does not care about whether they lose a single game or a gammon, but they have much to gain from winning a gammon; thus they can benefit from aggressive openings.<ref name=survey/>  The opposite may be true in "gammon-save" situations, where the player has little to lose from losing a single game, but much to lose from losing a gammon. At double-match-point (DMP) where the score is tied with each player needing one point to win, gammons do not matter for either player.

In practice, an even more important influencing factor is the preferred style of the player. A player might have a strong preference for one out of a number of alternative opening plays that are on average as effective, because the character of the move (passive or aggressive) better suits his or her playing style.<ref>Backgammon opening moves on Winning Backgammon</ref><ref>[http://www.backgammon.org/articles/backgammon-opening-rolls/ Opening rolls on Backgammon.org (1)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060824094629/http://www.backgammon.org/articles/backgammon-opening-rolls/ |date=2006-08-24 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.backgammon.org/articles/backgammon-opening-rolls-2/ |title=Opening rolls on Backgammon.org (2) |access-date=2006-08-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060824100205/http://www.backgammon.org/articles/backgammon-opening-rolls-2/ |archive-date=2006-08-24 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.backgammon.org/articles/backgammon-opening-rolls-3/ |title=Opening rolls on Backgammon.org (3) |access-date=2006-08-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060824100217/http://www.backgammon.org/articles/backgammon-opening-rolls-3/ |archive-date=2006-08-24 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.backgammon.org/articles/backgammon-opening-rolls-4/ |title=Opening rolls on Backgammon.org (4) |access-date=2006-08-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060824100229/http://www.backgammon.org/articles/backgammon-opening-rolls-4/ |archive-date=2006-08-24 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>

