'''Bangladeshi animation''' is still a new form of visual arts but experiencing a rapid growth. The animation industry employs about 12,000 people of different ages in [[Bangladesh]]. Most of the animation works are of outsourced projects from western developed nations. Other animation works include projects related to social awareness related programs and for TV advertisement purposes. Few animation studios are also producing animated short and feature films.<ref>{{cite AV media | url=http://www.aljazeera.com/video/asia/2014/02/bangladesh-animation-industry-growing-20142184718988970.html | title=Bangladesh animation industry growing | publisher=[[Al Jazeera English]] | date=18 February 2014 | people=[[Rob Reynolds (journalist)|Rob Reynolds]] | location=Dhaka, Bangladesh}}</ref> There are some animation festivals that annually take place in Bangladesh, most prominently the [[International Animation and Cartoon Festival]].

== History ==
Bangladeshi animation traces its origin in the 1980s when the National Institute of Mass Communications started to offer courses on animation. The first major animation project in Bangladesh was a cartoon series titled ''[[Meena (TV series)|Meena]]'', developed as part of some social awareness programs in partnership with [[UNICEF]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Meena is for all|url=http://www.unicef.org/bangladesh/media_2140.htm|publisher=UNICEF|accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref>  Meena was first released in 1993 and became a household name across Bangladeshi children.<ref>{{cite web|title=Meena and UNICEF|url=http://www.unicef.org/bangladesh/kidsspace_5104.htm|publisher=[[UNICEF]]|accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref> In 2000, another animated television series was released titled ''[[The Adventures of Montu Miah]]'' which became hugely popular within a short time. In 2013, the first edition of ''International Animation Cartoon Festival Bangladesh'', the only major animated film festival in Bangladesh, took place at the [[Shishu Academy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=3-day animation fest features local, foreign cartoons |url=http://www.newagebd.com/detail.php?date=2013-03-31&nid=44547 |accessdate=26 April 2014 |newspaper=New Age |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426234944/http://www.newagebd.com/detail.php?date=2013-03-31&nid=44547 |archivedate=26 April 2014 }}</ref>  The production of the first Bangladeshi animated feature film, titled ''[[The Dreamstage]]'', began in 2013 which is set to release in mid-2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=‘The Dreamstage’ to be BD’s first animated feature film|url=http://www.banglanews24.com/English/detailsnews.php?%20%20%20nssl=8e96206c19fa335a98b84093a2af34e1&nttl=0109201376492|accessdate=26 April 2014|newspaper=Banglanews24.com}}</ref>

Magic Puppet Studio is one of the  major private animation studio in Bangladesh which was established in 2015 [www.mpvfx.com] . [http://archive.thedailystar.net/beta2/news/animations-and-much-more/ Cartoon Bangladesh] has started its journey since 2008. [[ToonBangla]], a prominent Bangladeshi animation studio was founded in 2005. In 2010, [[Ogniroth Studio]] was founded which later became one of the major animation studios in the country.<ref>{{cite news|title=Exclusive enterprising entrepreneurs|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/weekend/2014/jan/04/exclusive-enterprising-entrepreneurs|accessdate=26 April 2014|newspaper=Dhaka Tribune}}</ref>

